# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1997-summer-universiade
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1975-summer-universiade] The **1975 Summer Universiade**, also known as the VIII Summer Universiade, took place in Rome, Italy.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1975-summer-universiade] The 1975 Universiade only featured athletics, other disciplines having been cancelled, as the original host Yugoslavia was unable to hold the event.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1975-summer-universiade] It was therefore referred to as the World University Championships in athletics.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] The **1983 Summer Universiade**, also known as the **XII Summer Universiade**, took place in Edmonton, Alberta, Canada between July 1 and 12, 1983.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] Over 2,400 athletes from 73 countries participated.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] It was the first ever Summer Universiade held in North America; as of 2026, it remains the only time Canada hosted the Summer, or Winter, Universiade (renamed Summer, or Winter, World University Games in 2021).
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] Previously, Edmonton hosted the 1978 Commonwealth Games, and later hosted the 2001 World Championships in Athletics, amongst other international sporting events.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] The official mascot of the event was Wugie the Owl; his name is an acronym of World University Games in Edmonton, and the Owl is the provincial bird of Alberta.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] The Prince of Wales (now Charles III) opened the Universiade accompanied by Diana, Princess of Wales, and other dignitaries and celebrities also visited the event.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] The event was marred by tragedy from the death of Soviet diver Sergei Chalibashvili when he died eight days after hitting his head on the 10 m diving platform in competition while attempting a reverse 3½ in the tuck position.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] In October 2005, Edmonton was selected as a potential bid candidate to host the 2011 Summer Universiade by the Canadian Interuniversity Sport (CIS).
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1983-summer-universiade] Around 2,400 athletes from 73 nations, competed at the 1983 Summer Universiade.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] The **1985 Summer Universiade**, also known as the XIII Summer Universiade, took place in Kobe, Japan.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] The mascot of the Kobe Universiade, "Unitan", designed by Osamu Tezuka, is a red-crested white crane, symbolic of Japan and a good omen.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] The name was chosen from some 8,000 suggestions received from throughout the country.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] The name is derived from a combination of 'uni' from 'Universiade' and 'tan' from the Japanese name for red-crested crane, namely 'tancho-tsuru'.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] The sex chromatin test was used at these games to decide on participants' gender; Spanish hurdler Maria José Martínez-Patiño was declared a man and thus ruled ineligible for the women's events.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] In agreement with officials who suggested she fake an injury so she could withdraw without publicity, she complied.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1985-summer-universiade] She later fought, successfully, to have that diagnosis reversed.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] The **1987 Summer Universiade**, also known as the **XIV Summer Universiade**, took place in Zagreb, SR Croatia, SFR Yugoslavia.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] It involved participants from 111 countries and over 6,000 individual sportspersons and members from delegations.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] The City of Zagreb used the event to renovate and revitalize the city.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] The city's main square (Republic Square) was repaved with stone blocks and made part of the downtown pedestrian zone.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] A part of the Medveščak stream, which had been running under the sewers since 1898, was uncovered by workers.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] This part formed the Manduševac fountain that was also covered in 1898.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] Multi-sport venue ŠRC Jarun on the Jarun Lake was built for the event.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1987-summer-universiade] The mascot of the 1987 Summer Universiade is a squirrel, named "Zagi" and created by Nedeljko Dragić.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1989-summer-universiade] The **1989 Summer Universiade**, also known as the XV Summer Universiade, took place in Duisburg, West Germany.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1989-summer-universiade] It was a scaled-down event with only four sports after the original hosts, Brazil, were forced to pull out due to a mounting financial crisis in that country.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1989-summer-universiade] A total of 1785 athletes from 79 nations participated in the event organized by the International University Sports Federation.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The **1991 Summer Universiade**, officially known as the XVI Summer Universiade and generally referred to as the **World Student Games**, were held in Sheffield, England from 14 to 25 July 1991.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The Games were the largest sporting event to be hosted in the United Kingdom since the 1948 Summer Olympics.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Sheffield City Council saw the event as a catalyst for urban renewal and regeneration after industrial decline.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] It set up a company, Universiade GB Ltd, to run the games.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] New facilities built for the event included the centrepiece Don Valley Stadium and other arenas, while the Lyceum Theatre was renovated for the associated cultural events.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] More than 3,300 athletes took part from 101 countries, including the first appearance of a unified German team at a Summer Universiade.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Sheffield was selected as the host for the 1991 Summer Universiade at an annual meeting of FISU's (Federation Internationale du Sport Universitaire) Executive Committee in the city in February 1987.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Despite initial excitement, lack of central government funding and sponsorship led to the organising company, Universiade GB, going into liquidation in the summer of 1990 with debts of more than £1 million.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Sheffield City Council stepped in to run the games using taxpayer money.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The three major venues for the events were all built especially for the event, on land formerly occupied by various industrial works.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Don Valley Stadium, the centrepiece for the Games, was completed in September 1990, at a cost of £29 million.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] It was the first entirely new outdoor sporting arena built in Great Britain since Wembley in 1923.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] With a capacity of 25,000, it was twice as large as the second-biggest athletics arena in the country, Crystal Palace.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Ponds Forge, named for the former steelworks demolished to make way for it, hosted the aquatics events.The Sheffield Arena opened in May 1991 as a multi-purpose venue and hosted the gymnastics events.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Other venues included the Concord Sports Center in Shiregreen and Hillsborough Stadium.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The football tournament was held across Yorkshire; at Huddersfield, Chesterfield, Wakefield, Bradford, Scunthorpe and Stocksbridge,with some games played at the Hillsborough.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Hyde Park flats near Sheffield City Centre were used for accommodation for the athletes during the games.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Built in the 1960s, many had been demolished, with those left being specially refurbished for the Games.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The medals were forged by Thessco, a Sheffield-based mint, who charged no fee for their manufacture.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The medals' designs were selected through a national student competition, and the final design bore the Yorkshire Rose.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The organisers struggled to find a live broadcast partner with any of the three terrestrial networks so a deal was signed with BSB (British Satellite Broadcasting) and Sky Sports provided extensive live coverage of the event.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] However, at the time only 1.5 million households had access to satellite television, thus reducing the potential audience.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Highlights were shown on Yorkshire Television, with commentary from John Helm and Gary Bloom.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The opening ceremony included a performance honouring Sheffield's industrial heritage, with participants wearing flat caps and waistcoats and carrying hammers, choreographed by Judy Chabola, who had been involved with the opening ceremony of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Sheffield native Helen Sharman, Britain's first astronaut, attracted publicity when she tripped and dropped the games torch, extinguishing it; the flames were lit by the ignitor in the flame bowl itself.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The Games were then officially opened by Princess Anne.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Despite the initial high hopes that the Games would foster regeneration in the city, heavy financial losses continue to burden the Games' legacy.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Whilst the event cost a reported £10 million to host at the time, with building costs predicted to reach only £25 million, by the opening ceremony construction had already cost £174 million.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Loans taken out to build the three main arenas - Don Valley Stadium, Ponds Forge International Sports Centre and Sheffield Arena - have been refinanced four times in the years since, with the final cost coming to £658 million when it is paid off in 2024.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The World Student Games, documented by one of the on site volunteers, Linda Stewart Pitts (Mother of writer and photographer Johny Pitts) appeared as a zine published by Café Royal Books in 2025.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The Don Valley Stadium was used in later years for a variety of events, including rugby league, American football and as Rotherham United's home ground during the construction of New York Stadium.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] It was demolished due to budget cuts in 2013.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The Sheffield Arena constructed for the games became the home of the Sheffield Steelers Ice hockey team in 1991, in an attempt to find a long term use for the venue.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] Games continue to be played by the team.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-summer-universiade] The 1991 Summer Universiade remains the only time that the Games have taken place in the United Kingdom.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-winter-universiade] The **1991 Winter Universiade**, the XV Winter Universiade, took place in Sapporo, Japan.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1991-winter-universiade] It was the first Winter Universiade to be held in Asia.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1997-summer-universiade] The **1997 Summer Universiade**, also known as the XIX Summer Universiade, took place in the island of Sicily, Italy.
[src:1997-summer-universiade/1997-summer-universiade] The United States topped the medal table.
